th wonderful handcrafts and patterns, makes it a beautiful location. So, individuals looking for some ancient buildings to explore can reach out to this place to enjoy its stunning architecture and surroundings. 14. Tsunami Monument in Kanyakumari The monument was constructed in honour of all who suffered in the tragic massive earthquake that occurred on December 26, 2004. The two-arm, 16-foot monument is situated close to the city's southern boundary. The light is blazing on the right hand, and a vast blue wave stops it with the left hand to keep it from going out. This monument is undoubtedly a must-see location since it stands for bravery and perseverance in the face of adversity. From November through March, you may visit this place. You should include this place in your tourist spot list and make sure you pay tribute there to those people who were killed. Best Time To Visit Kanyakumari Since the climate is quiet and comfortable from October to February, it is the perfect time to visit Kanyakumari. The optimum time to take in dawn, dusk, and ocean activities at this place is this time. Maximum temperatures in Kanyakumari range from 20 to 35 ° in the summer, 24 to 31 degrees during the monsoon, and 17 to 32 degrees in the winter. Preferably go between October and February if you plan a trip to Kanyakumari. Local Food In Kanyakumari The heart of outstanding South Indian cuisines is Kanyakumari. The cuisine of Kanyakumari used to be flavorful, fiery, and refreshing. It is recognized for its seafood and traditional South Indian cuisines like dosa and idli. Somiya, Kothu, Banana Chips, Appam, and Marwaji Kilangu with fish are some of the delicious local foods of Kanyakumari. You must try it if you are visiting Kanyakumari. Way To Reach Kanyakumari Trivandrum International Airport, which is 67 kilometres from Kanyakumari, is the closest airport to the city. It has good air connections to certain Gulf nations and the major Indian cities. To get to this airport, there a