 which attracts visitors with more than 100 different tree species and animals, ducks, and birds. So make sure you include this tourist destination in your list to enjoy its beauty and calmness. 2. Kanyakumari Beach in Kanyakumari Besides being an excellent site for a camping trip, Kanyakumari Beach is also a place of worship. It is located near the southernmost point of peninsular India. The morning and evening views of Kanyakumari Beach are magnificent. Many people used to gather here to view this beauty, especially during full moon day, which mostly happens in April. Kanyakumari Beach is a gorgeous spot to watch out as the waters of the Bay of Bengal, Arabian Sea, and the Indian Ocean used to converge here. This beach is well known for its vibrant and bright sands. 3. Kanyakumari Temple in Kanyakumari One of the primaries draws to this city is Kanyakumari Temple. Kanyakumari Bhagavathiamman Temple is another name for it. The Pandya dynasty rulers initially constructed the Kumari Amman Temple in the eighth century, and the Vijayanagara, Chola, and Nayaka emperors later restored it. As per legend, it is said that because Goddess Kanyakumari and Lord Shiva's marriage didn't happen, the Goddess decided to remain a virgin. The rice and other grains intended for the wedding are thought to have been left undercooked and turned into stones. Even today, grains-shaped rocks are still visible. So if you are a follower of God and willing to explore the related sites, this is the most important place to explore. 4. Gandhi Mandapam in Kanyakumari Gandhi Mandapam is a monument created in 1956 to honour the outstanding national leader. Before being buried in the sea, our nation's Father, Gandhi's ashes were held here. After the leader passed away, his cremated remains were partitioned among 12 urns and dispersed across the country so that people could pay their final respects to this significant figure. Due to Gandhi's connections to Kanyakumari, building a monument there in his honour may have been necessary. One of the most revered locations to visit in Kanyakumari is Gandhi Mandapam. The monument's centre pillar, which stands 79 feet tall and represents the Mahatma's age at the time of his assassination, is what makes it unique. So make sure you include this tourist destination in your list to pay tribute to our nation's father here. 5. Vivekananda Rock Memorial in Kanyakumari Swami Vivekananda, a follower of Sri Ramakrishna Paramahansa and the founder of the Ramakrishna Mission, is honoured at the gorgeous Vivekananda Memorial Rock. The red and blue granite that makes up the Vivekananda Rock Memorial was erected between 1963 and 1970. Vivekananda Mandapam and Sripada Mandapam are the two primary buildings that make up the Vivekananda Rock Memorial. On the Shripada Parai, which has Kanyakumari Devi's imprint, is where the Shripada Mandapam is located. It is thought that Swami Vivekananda utilized this location for meditation. So if you admire Swami Vivekanand for any reason, you should surely visit this place to learn a few more about him. 6. Kamarajar Manimandapam in Kanyakumari In honour of Sri Kamaraj, the previous Chief Minister of Tamil Nadu and a leader in the country's struggle for independence, Kamarajar Manimandapam was constructed. Near the Mahatma Gandhi Memorial, Kamarajar Manimandapam is also located. On the exact spot where his ashes were placed, a monument was erected so that people could pay respects to him by remembering him. The general public referred to Shri Kamarajar as "Black Gandhi." So, people visiting Kanyakumari should explore this place to know more about the former Chief Minister of Tamil Nadu. 7. Tiruchendur Temple in Kanyakumari Around 80 kilometres from Kanyakumari, 60 kilometres from Tirunelveli, and 40 kilometres from Tuticorin, the Tiruchendur Arulmigu Subramanyaswamy Temple is situated in the town of Tiruchendur. The second home of Lord Murugan is this temple, also known as Santhilandvar. The place where the Tiruchendur Murugan Temple is located is a hill known as Chandana Hill. After killing the monster Sorapadma, Lord Murugan is said to have worshipped Lord Shiva here. So if you are a follower of God and willing to explore the related sites, this is the most important place to explore. 8. Our Lady of Ransom Church in Kanyakumari The Kanyakumari region of Tamil Nadu is home to the well-known Catholic church known as Our Lady of Ransom, which is named after Mother Mary. The church was built in the Gothic style around the fifteenth century. Beautiful wood sculptures of the twelve disciples, angels playing stringed instruments, and Mother Mary being crowned may be seen on the walls and ceilings. This church seems in its entire splendour when lighted up every night. One of Kanyakumari's top architectural attractions is the Our Lady of Ransom Church. It is among the top tourist destinations in Kanyakumari. So make sure you include this tourist destination in your list to enjoy its beauty and calmness. 9. Vattakottai Fort in Kanyakumari In Tamil Nadu, Vattakottai fort lies at the southernmost point of India. The former Kingdom of Travancore constructed it in the 18th century as shore protection and barracks. The Fort is mainly built of granite stones, and presently a portion of it even reaches the sea. The Indian Archaeological Department has just completed a significant renovation of the Fort, which is now designated as a tourist spot. The massive Fort became a popular tourist site because of its historical significance and breathtaking surroundings. This location is enthralling due to the gorgeous highlands of the Bay of Bengal on one side, the Western Ghats on the other, and beaches fringed with brilliant black sand. Buses to and from the Fort run regularly thanks to Kanyakumari Road Transport Corporation. 10. Thiruvalluvar Statue in Kanyakumari The Tirukkural, early Tamil literature on religion and morality, was written by the writer and philosopher Valluvar and i