im. The general public referred to Shri Kamarajar as "Black Gandhi." So, people visiting Kanyakumari should explore this place to know more about the former Chief Minister of Tamil Nadu. 7. Tiruchendur Temple in Kanyakumari Around 80 kilometres from Kanyakumari, 60 kilometres from Tirunelveli, and 40 kilometres from Tuticorin, the Tiruchendur Arulmigu Subramanyaswamy Temple is situated in the town of Tiruchendur. The second home of Lord Murugan is this temple, also known as Santhilandvar. The place where the Tiruchendur Murugan Temple is located is a hill known as Chandana Hill. After killing the monster Sorapadma, Lord Murugan is said to have worshipped Lord Shiva here. So if you are a follower of God and willing to explore the related sites, this is the most important place to explore. 8. Our Lady of Ransom Church in Kanyakumari The Kanyakumari region of Tamil Nadu is home to the well-known Catholic church known as Our Lady of Ransom, which is named after Mother Mary. The church was built in the Gothic style around the fifteenth century. Beautiful wood sculptures of the twelve disciples, angels playing stringed instruments, and Mother Mary being crowned may be seen on the walls and ceilings. This church seems in its entire splendour when lighted up every night. One of Kanyakumari's top architectural attractions is the Our Lady of Ransom Church. It is among the top tourist destinations in Kanyakumari. So make sure you include this tourist destination in your list to enjoy its beauty and calmness. 9. Vattakottai Fort in Kanyakumari In Tamil Nadu, Vattakottai fort lies at the southernmost point of India. The former Kingdom of Travancore constructed it in the 18th century as shore protection and barracks. The Fort is mainly built of granite stones, and presently a portion of it even reaches the sea. The Indian Archaeological Department has just completed a significant renovation of the Fort, which is now designated as a tourist spot. The massive Fort became a popular 