cks, and birds. So make sure you include this tourist destination in your list to enjoy its beauty and calmness. 2. Kanyakumari Beach in Kanyakumari Besides being an excellent site for a camping trip, Kanyakumari Beach is also a place of worship. It is located near the southernmost point of peninsular India. The morning and evening views of Kanyakumari Beach are magnificent. Many people used to gather here to view this beauty, especially during full moon day, which mostly happens in April. Kanyakumari Beach is a gorgeous spot to watch out as the waters of the Bay of Bengal, Arabian Sea, and the Indian Ocean used to converge here. This beach is well known for its vibrant and bright sands. 3. Kanyakumari Temple in Kanyakumari One of the primaries draws to this city is Kanyakumari Temple. Kanyakumari Bhagavathiamman Temple is another name for it. The Pandya dynasty rulers initially constructed the Kumari Amman Temple in the eighth century, and the Vijayanagara, Chola, and Nayaka emperors later restored it. As per legend, it is said that because Goddess Kanyakumari and Lord Shiva's marriage didn't happen, the Goddess decided to remain a virgin. The rice and other grains intended for the wedding are thought to have been left undercooked and turned into stones. Even today, grains-shaped rocks are still visible. So if you are a follower of God and willing to explore the related sites, this is the most important place to explore. 4. Gandhi Mandapam in Kanyakumari Gandhi Mandapam is a monument created in 1956 to honour the outstanding national leader. Before being buried in the sea, our nation's Father, Gandhi's ashes were held here. After the leader passed away, his cremated remains were partitioned among 12 urns and dispersed across the country so that people could pay their final respects to this significant figure. Due to Gandhi's connections to Kanyakumari, building a monument there in his honour may have been necessary. One of the most revered locations to visit in Kanyakumari is Gandhi Mandapam. The monument's centre pillar, which stands 79 feet tall and represents the Mahatma's age at the time of his assassination, is what makes it unique. So make sure you include this tourist destination in your list to pay tribute to our nation's father here. 5. Vivekananda Rock Memorial in Kanyakumari Swami Vivekananda, a follower of Sri Ramakrishna Paramahansa and the founder of the Ramakrishna Mission, is honoured at the gorgeous Vivekananda Memorial Rock. The red and blue granite that makes up the Vivekananda Rock Memorial was erected between 1963 and 1970. Vivekananda Mandapam and Sripada Mandapam are the two primary buildings that make up the Vivekananda Rock Memorial. On the Shripada Parai, which has Kanyakumari Devi's imprint, is where the Shripada Mandapam is located. It is thought that Swami Vivekananda utilized this location for meditation. So if you admire Swami Vivekanand for any reason, you should surely visit this place to learn a few more about him. 6. Kamarajar Manimandapam in Kanyakumari In honour of Sri Kamaraj, the previous Chief Minister of Tamil Nadu and a leader in the country's struggle for independence, Kamarajar Manimandapam was constructed. Near the Mahatma Gandhi Memorial, Kamarajar Manimandapam is also located. On the exact spot where his ashes were placed, a monument was erected so that people could pay respects to him by remembering him. The general public referred to Shri Kamarajar as "Black Gandhi." So, people visiting Kanyakumari should explore this place to know more about the former Chief Minister of Tamil Nadu. 7. Tiruchendur Temple in Kanyakumari Around 80 kilometres from Kanyakumari, 60 kilometres from Tirunelveli, and 40 kilometres from Tuticorin, the Tiruchendur Arulmigu Subramanyaswamy Temple is situated in the town of Tiruchendur. The second home of Lord Murugan is this temple, also known as Santhilandvar. The place where the Tiruchendur Murugan Temple is located is a hill known as Chandana Hill. After killing the monster Sorapadma, Lord Murugan is said to have worshipped Lord Shiva here. So if you are a follower of God and willing to explore the related sites, this is the most important place to explore. 8. Our Lady of Ransom Church in Kanyakumari The Kanyakumari region of Tamil Nadu is home to the well-known Catholic church known as Our Lady of Ransom, which is named after Mother Mary. The church was built in the Gothic style around the fifteenth century. Beautiful wood sculptures of the twelve disciples, angels playing stringed instruments, and Mother Mary being crowned may be seen on the walls and ceilings. This church seems in its entire splendour when lighted up every night. One of Kanyakumari's top architectural attractions is the Our Lady of Ransom Church. It is among the top tourist destinations in Kanyakumari. So make sure you include this tourist destination in your list to enjoy its beauty and calmness. 9. Vattakottai Fort in Kanyakumari In Tamil Nadu, Vattakottai fort lies at the southernmost point of India. The former Kingdom of Travancore constructed it in the 18th century as shore protection and barracks. The Fort is mainly built of granite stones, and presently a portion of it even reaches the sea. The Indian Archaeological Department has just completed a significant renovation of the Fort, which is now designated as a tourist spot. The massive Fort became a popular tourist site because of its historical significance and breathtaking surroundings. This location is enthralling due to the gorgeous highlands of the Bay of Bengal on one side, the Western Ghats on the other, and beaches fringed with brilliant black sand. Buses to and from the Fort run regularly thanks to Kanyakumari Road Transport Corporation. 10. Thiruvalluvar Statue in Kanyakumari The Tirukkural, early Tamil literature on religion and morality, was written by the writer and philosopher Valluvar and is honoured by the 133-foot-tall Thiruvalluvar Statue. Construction of the monument started in 1990 and was devotedly pursued until 1999, when it was managed to finish. The statue is now India's 25th highest statue. It is a landmark of significant cultural significance and one of the most visited attractions in Kanyakumari. The figure is close to the Vivekananda Rock Memorial and is accessible from the coastline by boat services. 11. Thirparappu falls in Kanyakumari Thirparappu Falls, located around 55 kilometres from Kanyakumari, are spectacular. This 50-foot-tall artificial waterfall is artificial, and it combines many streams of water pouring from above to create a magnificent water pool below. A nature lover's heaven, the waterfalls are covered with dense green vegetation and local wildlife. You can photograph the fascinating scenes of the icy waterfalls plunging to the ground. It's the ideal location for a family holiday or a picnic with family members and friends. So explore this beautiful natural sight without fail. It will surely leave you surprised and will call you back after some time. 12. Thanumalayan Temple in Kanyakumari An important Hindu shrine called Thanumalayan Temple may be found in Tamil Nadu's Suchindram district of Kanyakumari. Even though the shrine is currently located in Tamil Nadu due to the community of Kanyakumari merging with Tamil Nadu, it is one of the 108 Shiva temples treasured by Kerala Hindu tradition. Trimuthis are honoured in the ancient shrine known as Thanumalayan Temple, often referred to as Sthanumalayan. With inscriptions from the ninth century, the stunning temple underwent renovation in the seventeenth century. The melodic pillars of the temple, which show off the artisans' construction ability, are its primary draw. There are four 18-foot-tall pillars, one of which is built of granite stone. The many temple pillars also include themes from the Mahabharata and Ramayana. So make sure you have this tourist destination on your list to enjoy its beauty and calmness. 13. Padmanabhapuram Palace in Kanyakumari A palace from the Travancore era, Padmanabhapuram Palace is situated in Tamil Nadu's Kanyakumari district. The distance to Kanyakumari City is roughly 39 kilometres. The administration of the nearby state of Kerala owns, runs, and maintains the palace. The old Hindu kingdom of Travancore, also known as Kalkulam Palace, had its capital in Padmanabhapuram. The Padmanabhapuram Palace said to have been constructed in the 16th century, is the repository of several rare antiques and artefacts. The grandeur of the palace itself, decorated with wonderful handcrafts and patterns, makes it a beautiful location. So, individuals looking for some ancient buildings to explore can reach out to this place to enjoy its stunning architecture and surroundings. 14. Tsunami Monument in Kanyakumari The monument was constructed in honour of all who suffered in the tragic massive earthquake that occurred on December 26, 2004. The two-arm, 16-foot monument is situated close to the city's southern boundary. The light is blazing on the right hand, and a vast blue wave stops it with the left hand to keep it from going out. This monument is undoubtedly a must-see location since it stands for bravery and perseverance in the face of adversity. From November through March, you may visit this place. You should include this place in your tourist spot list and make sure you pay tribute there to those people who were killed. Best Time To Visit Kanyakumari Since the climate is quiet and comfortable from October to February, it is the perfect time to visit Kanyakumari. The optimum time to take in dawn, dusk, and ocean activities at this place is this time. Maximum temperatures in Kanyakumari range from 20 to 35 ° in the summer, 24 to 31 degrees during the monsoon, and 17 to 32 degrees in the winter. Preferably go between October and February if you plan a trip to Kanyakumari. Local Food In Kanyakumari The heart of outstanding South Indian cuisines is Kanyakumari. The cuisine of Kanyakumari used to be flavorful, fiery, and refreshing. It is recognized for its seafood and traditional South Indian cuisines like dosa and idli. Somiya, Kothu, Banana Chips, Appam, and Marwaji Kilangu with fish are some of the delicious local foods of Kanyakumari. You must try it if you are visiting Kanyakumari. Way To Reach Kanyakumari Trivandrum International Airport, which is 67 kilometres from Kanyakumari, is the closest airport to the city. It has good air connections to certain Gulf nations and the major Indian cities. To get to this airport, there are several significant Indian airlines. In addition, several buses operated by Kanyakumari Road Transport travel to Kanyakumari from Tamil Nadu, Trivandrum, Chennai, and Bangalore. You may also take the Kanyakumari Express to get here from Bengaluru and Mumbai. You may take a cab from Kanyakumari, a significant railway station, to reach Kanyakumari city. Next TopicTourist Places in Mount Abu ? prev next ? For Videos Join Our Youtube Channel: Join Now Feedback Send your Feedback to [email protected] Help Others, Please Share Learn Latest Tutorials Splunk SPSS Swagger Transact-SQL Tumblr ReactJS Regex Reinforcement Learning R Programming RxJS React Native Python Design Patterns Python Pillow Python Turtle Keras Preparation Aptitude Reasoning Verbal Ability Interview Questions Company Questions Trending Technologies Artificial Intelligence AWS Selenium Cloud Computing Hadoop ReactJS Data Science Angular 7 Blockchain Git Machine Learning DevOps B.Tech / MCA DBMS Data Structures DAA Operating System Computer Network Compiler Design Computer Organization Discrete Mathematics Ethical Hacking Computer Graphics Software Engineering Web Technology Cyber Security Automata C Programming C++ Java .Net Python Programs Control System Data Mining Data Warehouse Javatpoint Services JavaTpoint offers too many high quality services. Mail us on [email protected], to get more information about given services. Website Designing Website Development Java Deve